## 3 Carat Pear Shaped Diamond Engagement Ring

The 3ct pear diamond is a rare-tier purchase. The stone dimensions at 3ct (approximately 13mm × 8.5mm at a 1.58 L/W ratio) make it one of the most visually dominant engagement ring configurations available without entering truly bespoke territory.

At this weight, the natural vs. lab price difference is so large it warrants serious consideration: the 3ct natural D-FL pear on Blue Nile runs **[$93,910](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27216797?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)**. A 3ct lab-grown pear at D-VVS1 runs approximately $7,000–$9,000. The gap is not $10,000 — it is $85,000.

For most buyers in the 3ct range, the decision point is not natural vs. lab aesthetically (they are visually indistinguishable). It is whether the ring is primarily a jewelry piece or a financial asset. Natural 3ct pear diamonds hold and appreciate in value over decades. Lab-grown diamonds at this weight do not — lab prices have fallen dramatically and are expected to continue declining.

**Setting for a 3ct pear diamond engagement ring:**

A 3ct pear stone should be set in a design that does not fight for attention with the stone. The French Pavé Engagement Ring in platinum at **[$3,925](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/french-pave-diamond-engagement-ring-in-platinum-1-ct-tw-item-194406?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** — with pavé along the shank and a clean, elevated basket — provides the right level of setting interest without competing with a 13mm stone.

Custom platinum settings built specifically for 3ct+ pear diamonds are also an option. Most high-end jewelers can build a bespoke platinum V-prong solitaire with a tapered shank for $3,000–$6,000 that is architecturally correct for the stone's scale.

