## The Carat Ladder: Buying at the Right Tier

The Carat Ladder is the single most important framework for pear diamond engagement ring budget decisions. It describes the three natural tiers where visible presence makes a meaningful jump — and the in-between zones where spending more money delivers no visible upgrade.

**Tier 1: 0.90ct–1.10ct.** This is the 1ct visual tier. Face-up size: approximately 8mm × 5mm. On the finger: clear, distinct diamond presence visible across a table. Under 0.90ct, the pear looks fashion-ring-sized. Above 1.10ct, you are paying a weight premium without leaving this visual tier.

**Tier 2: 1.80ct–2.10ct.** This is the 2ct visual tier. Face-up size: approximately 10.5mm × 7mm. On the finger: statement-level presence that reads across the room. The jump from 1.10ct to 1.80ct is the most expensive weight zone in pear diamonds — you are paying for every fraction of a carat without a commensurate jump in visual impact.

**Tier 3: 2.80ct–3.20ct.** This is the 3ct visual tier. Face-up size: approximately 13mm × 8mm. On the finger: unmistakable, conversation-starting presence. A pear diamond at this size is among the largest conventional engagement ring stones in any shape.

[![Pear diamond engagement ring in white gold — clean classic solitaire design showing the elongated pear brilliant face-up](/images/pear-diamond-engagement-ring-classic-white-gold.avif)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
*A classic pear diamond engagement ring in white gold — the elongated teardrop silhouette delivers more face-up size per carat than any symmetrical cut. **[Shop pear engagement rings on Blue Nile →](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?MetalType=all&Diamonds=Dia&ShapeID=Pear&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)***

**The dead zones:** 1.10ct–1.79ct and 2.11ct–2.79ct are zones where you are spending above one tier without reaching the next. A 1.50ct pear looks noticeably larger than a 1ct pear, but the jump from 1.50ct to 2ct is also noticeable — and you paid for both gaps.

The professional buying rule: stay within each tier's optimal range. Target 0.95–1.05ct for the 1ct tier. Target 1.90–2.05ct for the 2ct tier. Target 2.90–3.10ct for the 3ct tier. Buy the best color and clarity within that range rather than carat weight above the tier ceiling.

